label chapter15:

    # [Scene: Reclaimed Pier | Late Morning]

    scene bg ch13_4001e7_1 at full_bg
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: The hollow clank of a hydraulic press somewhere down the pier; gulls argue over a scrap of foam]
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Sparse piano motif, minor, slow; a single sustained low note underneath]
    "You keep your journal closed against your chest because it makes the grief take a shape you can hold. The leather is damp where your thumb worried the twine. Up close, the branded panels are not"
    "just better-made versions of what you and your neighbors bolted together—there are logos, serial numbers, a tidy stamp that reads: “CoastGuard Systems — Municipal Partner.”"
    "Your hands smell of salt and welding flux from the nights you taught neighbors to splice metal. Now the metal is folded into someone else’s ledger. You walk the length of the pier with your boots"
    "leaving dark footprints on the reclaimed planks, and every step feels like a small, private accusation."

    scene bg ch13_4001e7_2 at full_bg
    "You flip the cover of the journal open with an index-finger ritual you have when you need to count things you won’t say aloud—names of the people who built overnight checkpoints, who passed tools from one"
    "porch to the next, who taught you how to make a brittle seal flex. The names are a list of tenderness. The list feels insufficient."
    "You hear a measured step behind you."
    show ilan_cortez at left:
        zoom 0.7

    ilan_cortez "I heard. I—' (He stops, as if the apology is a tool he is trying to fit into the right space.) 'I never meant for this to be taken."
    show ava_marin at right:
        zoom 0.7

    ava_marin "Taken.' (The word tastes like the exposed metal you used to hammer into place.) 'They reverse-engineered the joints. They put their stamp on what we braided out of rope and rust."
    "Ilan Cortez keeps his hands in his pockets. His vest is still damp from early-morning tests; the compass on his chain rubs against the fabric and gives a muted metallic whisper."

    ilan_cortez "I should have pushed for legal protection the moment we had the first successful cycle. I thought keeping it local—slow—would be safer. I misread the vector of how quickly somebody could scale it."

    ava_marin "You trusted networks. I trusted people. We thought different shields would keep the same thing safe."
    "Ilan Cortez exhales and the sound is small and precise, like someone sealing an envelope you cannot open. He steps closer so you can see the small smudge of grease at the corner of his mouth."

    ilan_cortez "I'm sorry, Ava. Truly."
    "You hold his apology in your mouth, turning it like a coin. Apologies are currency you have banked before—useful, but sometimes unable to replace what was taken."

    menu:
        "Touch the compass":
            "You close your fingers around the brass compass on his chain. It's warm from his body; the brass reads fingerprints like a map. You don't say anything—your fingers say it for you."
        "Step back and scold":
            "You step back, voice tight. 'Sorry doesn't weld bolts, Ilan.' Your tone is sharp enough to ring on the neighboring scaffolds. He flinches, and you hate that your voice made him smaller."

    menu:
        "Lean into him":
            "You fold into the warmth available. The hug is small and human—wet hair, the smell of solder and rain. For a moment the world withdraws, and you remember why you built anything at all: to make room for people."
        "Step away and list grievances":
            "You step away and list the practical failures—no legal cushion, no open records, no public timestamp. His face tightens at each item and you can see the weight of what you both lost settle onto him. The space between you widens."
    "THE END"
    # [GAME END]
    return
